Out of Memory events and decoding their logging

Oct 4, 2023Knowledge

Article Body

Summary: Explaining Out of Memory (OOM errors) and how to decode their logging.

In most Linux distributions, the kernel sets the default value of /proc/sys/vm/overcommit_memory to zero, so that processes can request more memory than is available in the system.

This is done based on the assumption that allocated memory is not fully used up immediately, and that processes, over their lifetime, also may not use all of the memory they allocate. Overcommitting memory allows the system to use the memory in a more efficient way but at the risk of OOM situations. When an OOM event occurs, it will cause an OOM-killer to kill the process which has scored the highest.

An OOM Killer is a function of the Linux kernel that is intended to kill rogue processes that are requesting more memory that the OS can allocate, so that the system can survive. The function applies some heuristics (it gives each process a score) to decide which process to kill when the system is in such a state. The process monopolizing the most amount of memory and not releasing enough of it is generally the most likely to be killed.

  • RedHat points out that when troubleshooting why the out of memory (OOM) killer process starts up, you should look at a few factors on the system. An OOM killer usually starts because of one of the following reasons:

    Reason

    Problem Cause

    1

    A spike in memory usage based on a load event (additional processes are needed for increased load).

    2

    A spike in memory usage based on additional services being added or migrated to the system. (Added another application or new service on the system has started)

    3

    A spike in memory usage due to failed hardware such as a DIMM memory module.

    4

    S spike in memory usage due to undersizing of hardware resources for the running application(s).

    5

    A memory leak in a running application.

    Possible reasons for OOM error appearing in the above scenarios:

    1. It is caused by the misconfiguration for application processes, the resolution is to tune the parameter of the applications;

    2. It is caused by a hardware issue, for example, DIMM memory module, the resolution is to replace the malfunctioning module;

    3. It is caused by the lack of total hardware resource, and the resolution is to allocate more memory resource or add swap space.

    4. It is caused by the memory leak.

    5. It is caused by memory fragmentation.

pid

The process ID.

uid

User ID.

tgid

Thread group ID.

total_vm

Virtual memory use (in 4 kB pages)

rss

Resident memory use (in 4 kB pages)

nr_ptes

Page table entries

swapents

Page table entries

oom_score_adj

Usually, 0. A lower number indicates the process will be less likely to die when the OOM killer is invoked.

The process that ends up with the highest OOM score is killedthats the "score" reported on the "Out of memory" line.

Decoding the information in the OOM log

The total RAM size is 9437070 pages (36GB) plus the total swap is 8191996kB (8.2GB) as virtual memory for all the processes running on the node, in the communication with customer we got to know that they have GitMS, GerritMS, MySql applications are running on the node, the memory assigned to GitMS (16GB), the memory assigned to GerritMS (16GB), the rest 4GB reserved by system.

Sum of all the total_vm is 20639222, and the sum of rss is 3182744, these two values are counted in 4kB pages, which means when OOM-killer was running, it has used 3182744*4kB=12.7GB physical memory and swap space. At that moment, the total swap has been used out (Free swap = 0kB), and there is no free memory in HighMem/Normal zone (0 pages HighMem/MovableOnly). Rss for process 6033 is 2656268, which means 2656268*4kB=10625072kB rss, was equal to sum of anon-rss and file-rss and shmem-rss.

Look back upon the circumstances when process telegraf was trying to request memory.

  1. The process telegraf was trying to request for 4kB memory (order=0 means one page), the memory would be allocated from HighMem/Normal zone. (The last 2 bits in gfp_mask 0x201da indicates this).

  2. We see that the free pages (33564kB) in HighMem/Normal zone is less than the min_pages watermark (33952kB) on NUMA Node 1. When the number of free pages reaches low_pages watermark, the kswapd will be woken up, and it would start to free up pages from zones, and once it further drops to min_pages watermark due to frequently memory request from processes, the process telegraf cannot allocate memory below min_pages watermark as those areas are reserved by kernel, also it would cause kernel to direct reclaim memory. Before this direct reclaim or during this time, it triggers oom killer to kill the process 6033 to release enough memory so that the system can be survival. (See below graph)

    Apr 14 14:13:33 sha2uvp-gert01 kernel: Node 1 Normal free:33564kB min:33952kB low:42440kB high:50928kB active_anon:2656400kB inactive_anon:567172kB active_file:1776kB inactive_file:9296kB

  3. Zones are allotted in the preferential order of Normal > DMA32 > DMA, since the memory was not able to allocate from HighMem/Normal zone as free pages were already below min_pages watermark, then the next zone is attempted. In the meantime before oom killer killing the process 6033, process telegraf was then trying to get the requested memory(one page) from DMA32 and DMA zones. For a memory request to be granted/allocated the following check must pass:

    low watermark + lowmem_reserve[2] < free pages - n pages
low watermark - is the low watermark value in the zone;
lowmem_reserve - is a buffer watermark value to protect lower zones;
n pages - is the number of pages requested, in this case, it is 1;

    Removed the unnecessary part in the OOM log:

    Apr 14 14:13:33 sha2uvp-gert01 kernel: Node 0 DMA free:15860kB min:56kB low:68kB high:84kB active_anon:0kB inactive_anon:0kB active_file:0kB
Apr 14 14:13:33 sha2uvp-gert01 kernel: lowmem_reserve[]: 0 2828 8827 8827
Apr 14 14:13:33 sha2uvp-gert01 kernel: Node 0 DMA32 free:37068kB min:10608kB low:13260kB high:15912kB active_anon:992088kB inactive_anon:335716kB
Apr 14 14:13:33 sha2uvp-gert01 kernel: lowmem_reserve[]: 0 0 5998 5998

    Allocate request to DMA32: a low watermark (13260kB) + lowmem_reserve[2] (5998, means 23992kB) > DMA32 free memory (37068kB) - 1 page (4kB), failed to get memory from DMA32.

  4. Then it was trying to get it from DMA Allocate request to DMA: low watermark (68kB) + lowmem_reserve[2] (8827, means 35308kB) > DMA free memory (15860kB) - 1 page (4kB), failed to get memory from DMA.

    Conclusion

    Theres nowhere to get the requested memory (4kB) at that moment from Normal zone on NUMA Node 1, DMA32 and DMA zones, even if the OOM-killer was not immediately triggered when a memory allocation request was to Normal zone (below min_pages watermark), it would be triggered when all zones have no memory to allocate.
